WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.000
[Music]

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.010
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. We're&nbsp;
moving to set up abstract algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.010 --> 00:00:22.140
and we've outlined some challenges that modern&nbsp;
treatment faces. This is our third challenge:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:27.540
the "fundamental dream of algebra," which is&nbsp;
usually known as the "fundamental theorem of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:34.410
algebra." Unfortunately, this is not really a&nbsp;
theorem currently. This is a very big topic;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.410 --> 00:00:41.400
it has huge implications throughout mathematics,&nbsp;
so it's a very foundational kind of issue and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:48.570
completely appropriate for this playlist, this&nbsp;
channel, where we're dealing with foundational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:55.170
issues. So the fundamental theorem of algebra—we&nbsp;
have to address some unpleasant, uncomfortable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.170 --> 00:01:00.660
truths about this very important and interesting&nbsp;
result, but it's logically problematic.

00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:06.810
Okay, so it's a fundamental result or claim&nbsp;
from undergraduate mathematics, and in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:12.120
there are a couple of different forms of the&nbsp;
fundamental theorem. I’d like to distinguish&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:17.340
between them by calling the first one the&nbsp;
fundamental theorem of algebra number one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.990 --> 00:01:28.170
It is that every polynomial P(x) equals a₀ +&nbsp;
a₁x + ... + aₙxⁿ (so this is a polynomial in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:35.430
x of degree n greater than or equal to one,&nbsp;
so there's at least a single x appearing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:44.880
somewhere) has a complex zero, R = a + bi.&nbsp;
What does that mean? It means that P(R) = 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:52.710
so it means that if you have a non-constant&nbsp;
polynomial, then you can find a complex number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:59.310
so that when you substitute that complex number&nbsp;
in for the x, then the total result is zero.

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:06.750
Okay, now we have to understand that these&nbsp;
coefficients that are appearing here are usually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.750 --> 00:02:13.170
taken to be real numbers, and the a and the b&nbsp;
appearing here in this description of complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:20.940
numbers are also taken to be real numbers. Now,&nbsp;
that, of course, is hugely problematic because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:26.580
there are all kinds of difficulties, as we've&nbsp;
seen, with the theory of real numbers. So that's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:32.250
big part of the problem, but there's more as well.&nbsp;
So this is the first version of the fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:37.560
theorem: that every non-constant polynomial&nbsp;
has a complex number zero or root.

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:44.700
And now here is the second version, or alternate&nbsp;
version, of the fundamental theorem of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:53.160
which asserts that a polynomial of degree&nbsp;
at least one can be factored as a product of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.160 --> 00:03:00.630
linear factors if we're allowing ourselves&nbsp;
complex coefficients. So it says that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:06.600
can find complex numbers R₁, R₂, up to Rₙ&nbsp;
(where n is the degree of the polynomial),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:12.840
and a lambda real number so that the&nbsp;
polynomial is actually equal to lambda&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:19.260
times the factor (x - R₁) times the factor (x&nbsp;
- R₂) all the way up to the factor (x - Rₙ),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:27.090
and these numbers are the zeros or the roots of&nbsp;
the polynomial. Clearly, if we replace x with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.090 --> 00:03:33.090
say, one of these R's, say R₁, then one of&nbsp;
these terms will be zero, and so the whole&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.090 --> 00:03:43.260
product will be zero. And as before here, all&nbsp;
these coefficients are generally real numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:51.000
although it turns out that there's a somewhat&nbsp;
more general version of this theorem which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.940
extends the same statements to the case where the&nbsp;
coefficients are not just so-called real numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.940 --> 00:04:02.850
but are in fact more general complex numbers&nbsp;
themselves, and the theorem still holds true.

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:09.420
So some of the ways that the fundamental theorem&nbsp;
of algebra ends up being used in undergraduate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:16.800
mathematics are through the consequence that if&nbsp;
you have a real polynomial, then you can deduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:22.770
that it factors into a product of linear and&nbsp;
quadratic factors, all of whose coefficients&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:27.970
are real numbers. So even if you're a little bit&nbsp;
unhappy about or unfamiliar with complex number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:34.420
arithmetic, a consequence of this is that if you&nbsp;
have an arbitrary polynomial with so-called real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:38.560
coefficients, or maybe rational coefficients,&nbsp;
then you could write it as a product of linear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:49.000
and quadratic factors all with real or possibly&nbsp;
rational coefficients, typically real. That has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.320
a lot of applications; for example, it's used&nbsp;
a lot to justify certain integration formulas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:02.920
using the idea of partial fractions. So it's&nbsp;
a key tool in the theory of integration,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:09.220
and it also allows all kinds of solutions to&nbsp;
various problems like recurrence relations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:16.450
differential equations, eigenvalue problems,&nbsp;
problems coming from combinatorics involving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.450 --> 00:05:21.850
generating functions, and other things too. So&nbsp;
there are quite a lot of situations where we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:28.000
need to find zeros of polynomials or we need&nbsp;
to factor polynomials, and it's always the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:37.360
fundamental theorem that is the workhorse that&nbsp;
lets us assert such zeros or factorizations.

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:46.000
But it's not just pure mathematics that uses this&nbsp;
kind of thinking. A lot of applied mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.900
leans very heavily on the fundamental theorem of&nbsp;
algebra. So there's a wide variety of problems&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.900 --> 00:06:01.990
coming from physics, engineering, chemistry,&nbsp;
and also economics and industry that one way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:10.570
or the other need to extract zeros of polynomials&nbsp;
and factorization. So here's a picture of a bunch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:17.140
of springs that separate masses M₁, M₂, M₃, and&nbsp;
M₄, and they're allowed to oscillate this way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:21.460
because they're these springs, and they have&nbsp;
different masses, and you might be interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:27.850
in understanding how these coupled oscillators&nbsp;
behave, okay? And that's a kind of problem that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:34.430
once you set it up in physics involves these&nbsp;
kinds of polynomials that have to be solved.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:40.700
There's a wide variety of such problems; for&nbsp;
example, Google's PageRank algorithm has some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:44.540
connection with this—neural nets, stress&nbsp;
matrices, rotations—you can give a very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:50.450
very long list of real-life applications,&nbsp;
ultimately, of the fundamental theorem of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.450 --> 00:06:57.260
algebra. So it's not just a theoretical tool; it's&nbsp;
also very important for practical applications.

00:06:57.260 --> 00:07:02.660
Now, for us, we're interested in setting up&nbsp;
abstract algebra, and so we have made the point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.660 --> 00:07:09.350
that in abstract algebra also, these theorems&nbsp;
play a very important role. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:15.440
the fundamental theorem really underpins&nbsp;
character theory for groups. So, if you want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:20.690
study group theory, non-commutative finite group&nbsp;
theory, there's a theory of characters, and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:26.900
fundamental theorem is intimately connected with&nbsp;
that theory. It's also the basis for much of field&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:33.740
theory. When we set up fields and look at concrete&nbsp;
examples of fields, and especially the associated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.740 --> 00:07:41.930
area called Galois theory, the fundamental theorem&nbsp;
and its role are so intimately woven into this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.930 --> 00:07:48.740
theory. It's very important for the structure&nbsp;
theory of matrices—matrices and the fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:55.670
theorem of algebra are intimately connected. For&nbsp;
example, Jordan canonical form and eigenvalue&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.670 --> 00:08:02.060
problems are all associated with this. But&nbsp;
it has a role in abstract algebra; algebraic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:10.760
number theory is very much relying on this kind&nbsp;
of thinking of the fundamental theorem because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:18.680
it tries to embed a lot of the fields and rings&nbsp;
that occur in number theory into complex numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:24.530
and that's essentially playing this game.&nbsp;
It also underpins the importance of complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:31.400
algebraic geometry. In algebraic geometry, we&nbsp;
study curves and higher-dimensional extensions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:37.430
called varieties, and for various technical&nbsp;
reasons, one likes to work over the complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.430 --> 00:08:44.640
numbers rather than more natural intuitive&nbsp;
sort of rational or real numbers. And a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:50.490
of the reason for that is because invoking&nbsp;
the fundamental theorem makes a lot of things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.490 --> 00:08:58.920
easier. This is a very common orientation in&nbsp;
algebraic geometry, again, ultimately coming&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:05.700
down to the fundamental theorem. So this is&nbsp;
a very important result for undergraduate and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:13.800
higher mathematics. It figures prominently in a&nbsp;
wide range of mathematics and also applications&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:21.630
to applied mathematics, but for us, it also&nbsp;
has a major input into abstract algebra.

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:31.170
So how sad is it that, in fact, these theorems&nbsp;
are actually seriously logically flawed? It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:35.490
very unfortunate, and it's something&nbsp;
that people, I know, would rather not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.490 --> 00:09:41.280
hear and would rather not learn about. They&nbsp;
would like to pretend that things are okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:45.420
but they are not, in fact, okay. Today,&nbsp;
there are serious problems, and in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:51.150
these theorems have to be recast, they have&nbsp;
to be rethought, and there's a lot of very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.150 --> 00:10:00.210
very important work and opportunities for young&nbsp;
people to come and to help in reconfiguring the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.210 --> 00:10:03.480
mathematics around the fundamental theorem of&nbsp;
algebra. So we're going to be talking about that.

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:09.780
So unfortunately, the reality is that the&nbsp;
fundamental theorem of algebra parts 1 &amp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:17.460
that we've discussed are actually dreams.&nbsp;
Currently, they are not real theorems—they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:23.760
are dreams. They are the result of wishful&nbsp;
thinking and insufficient attention paid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:33.870
to rigor and careful analysis. There are many&nbsp;
proofs of the fundamental theorem of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:41.250
and this was already one indicator of the logical&nbsp;
difficulties that the subject has. So many people&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:47.560
have come along and tried to pin down, first&nbsp;
of all, what this theorem is really about and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:53.500
then provide some kind of argument for it. Many&nbsp;
people have thought that they have an argument,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:57.340
and then later generations come along and say,&nbsp;
"Well, wait a minute, he was actually assuming&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.340 --> 00:11:01.930
something rather there, and that's not entirely&nbsp;
justified," and then they give a new proof,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:05.830
and then some decades later, someone comes&nbsp;
along and states the same thing about their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.830 --> 00:11:11.410
arguments. This has been going on for a long&nbsp;
time, going back probably first to D'Alembert,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:18.190
and Euler prominently was also very interested&nbsp;
in the fundamental theorem, and then Lagrange,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.190 --> 00:11:26.110
Galois, Cauchy, and Weierstrass. It's like a&nbsp;
who's who of famous mathematicians who tried&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:31.390
to understand what was really going on with this&nbsp;
fundamental theorem to try to provide proofs. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:39.940
it didn't stop with Weierstrass; many 20th-century&nbsp;
authors have also contributed new proofs. In fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:43.720
Gauss contributed to probably half a dozen proofs.&nbsp;
So he proved it, and then he would wait a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.720 --> 00:11:48.670
years and then come up with another proof. And&nbsp;
this probably gets him recognized that there was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:58.540
something not quite solid; there was a need for&nbsp;
further understanding because this topic touches&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:02.680
base with what I think is really the fundamental&nbsp;
problem in mathematics, which is the nature of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:07.930
continuum. And I'll talk about that more in my&nbsp;
next video, but the nature of the continuum is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.930 --> 00:12:12.880
actually a very subtle issue, and it's intimately&nbsp;
connected with the fundamental theorem of algebra.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:20.320
And so mathematicians have wrestled with this&nbsp;
for a long time, and I'm claiming that in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:28.090
unfortunately, all of these proofs or attempted&nbsp;
proofs are incomplete or wrong. Unfortunately,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:34.630
they don't really work. So even the current&nbsp;
statements of the theorems are faulty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:42.040
and you can see that in a simple way because if&nbsp;
you have a theorem that rests crucially on real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:48.040
numbers and you don't have a proper theory of real&nbsp;
numbers, well, then obviously you're in strife,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:56.660
and the fact that we don't have a proper theory&nbsp;
of real numbers almost immediately implies that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:56.660 --> 00:13:01.550
there's going to be problems with things like the&nbsp;
fundamental theorem of algebra that crucially rely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:01.550 --> 00:13:08.540
on properties of real numbers. But in fact, we&nbsp;
can see the problems in a much more direct way.

00:13:08.540 --> 00:13:14.630
So mathematics is not just about&nbsp;
theorizing and making abstract theories;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.630 --> 00:13:21.620
it's also about examples, explicit examples,&nbsp;
and concrete computations, and we don't want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.620 --> 00:13:27.350
to divorce ourselves from contact with these&nbsp;
explicit examples and concrete computations. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:27.350 --> 00:13:35.870
for example, most undergraduates don't really&nbsp;
see a proper proof of this fundamental theorem&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.870 --> 00:13:40.220
of algebra, even though they use it in&nbsp;
many, many, many places until perhaps in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:44.210
a third-year complex analysis course. So&nbsp;
there's usually a place somewhere after&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:50.480
you've done the real analysis where the proof&nbsp;
is presented, but it's almost always not very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:55.100
convincing to your typical undergraduate. They&nbsp;
go, "Okay, now I have some abstract argument&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:59.270
which I probably don't really believe," but&nbsp;
if there were really a convincing argument,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:04.700
then that convincing argument could be supported&nbsp;
by examples, right? So we give the argument,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:09.380
and then we can say, "And here, by the way, guys,&nbsp;
here are some examples of how it actually works."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:16.430
But unfortunately, the fundamental theorem&nbsp;
of algebra falls down as soon as you start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:21.050
looking at examples. You don't have to go very&nbsp;
far, and you see that, wait a minute, there is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:21.050 --> 00:14:27.710
some divergence between the claims that are made&nbsp;
and what actually happens in concrete situations.

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:34.610
Let me illustrate. Here is an example—there's&nbsp;
nothing particularly special about this example.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:34.610 --> 00:14:43.670
P(x) = x⁵ - 2x + 3. That's a polynomial of&nbsp;
degree 5; it has, in this case, integer entries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:49.820
so it's particularly simple. We can graph it, or&nbsp;
at least we can graph part of it. So it has some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:56.300
kind of shape like this for values, say, between&nbsp;
-3 and 3. We can see that it crosses the x-axis&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.300 --> 00:15:03.860
seemingly somewhere around here between -1 and -2.&nbsp;
It goes up here, has a little maximum there, then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:11.570
down to a minimum, and then it goes on together,&nbsp;
okay? So what's the claim here? The claim is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.570 --> 00:15:19.160
first of all, that this thing has a zero. We can&nbsp;
see that without using the fundamental theorem of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:24.020
algebra; we can see it from the picture, can't we?&nbsp;
And we're going back now to Newton's method—Newton&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:31.430
can see that there's a zero there, and to evaluate&nbsp;
that zero, he can create this algorithm that will,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:31.430 --> 00:15:38.180
well, not actually give you the zero but will&nbsp;
give you a sequence of approximations that will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:47.330
give you points on the x-axis that are closer and&nbsp;
closer to having the property that P(x) is zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:53.180
So we've talked about Newton's method, which is&nbsp;
very important, at some length earlier in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:53.180 --> 00:15:59.510
series. So the Math Foundations 83 up to 86, my&nbsp;
lectures, are all about that, and they give you a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.510 --> 00:16:08.270
way of successively creating a sequence of values&nbsp;
that are closer and closer to where this function&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.270 --> 00:16:14.540
ostensibly crosses the x-axis. So it certainly&nbsp;
suggests—the picture suggests—that yes, there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:14.540 --> 00:16:19.370
some point, but in fact, the actual logical&nbsp;
structure of that statement is not at all obvious.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.370 --> 00:16:27.650
It's not at all obviously clear that we understand&nbsp;
continuity well enough to really be able to assert&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:33.890
that there actually is an exact value of x for&nbsp;
which this polynomial takes on the value 0.

00:16:33.890 --> 00:16:41.750
Okay, but I can get my computer, I can set this&nbsp;
equal to 0, and I can ask my computer to solve it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:41.750 --> 00:16:49.580
and it will do so at least up to a certain&nbsp;
resolution that I can input beforehand. So if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:55.400
I ask it, say, for eight decimal places, something&nbsp;
like that, then it will tell me that a zero or a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:55.400 --> 00:17:04.760
solution to P(x) = 0 is, say, given by -1.4236058.&nbsp;
That, according to my computer, is a solution to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:13.190
the equation P(x) = 0. In other words, that's a&nbsp;
root or a zero of the polynomial. Great. But if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.190 --> 00:17:19.850
I want to check and I actually take this exact&nbsp;
value and plug it in here and get my computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.850 --> 00:17:26.600
to evaluate that, it does not give me zero.&nbsp;
It evaluates it again to eight decimal places&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.600 --> 00:17:39.410
as 8.9999626 x 10⁻⁷. That's a relatively small&nbsp;
quantity, but it's definitely not zero, all right?

00:17:39.410 --> 00:17:46.610
Then I can up the resolution, so I can go into my&nbsp;
program and ask it to evaluate things not to eight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:52.160
decimal places but to maybe 16 decimal places&nbsp;
or something like that. Okay, so I've done that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.160 --> 00:18:01.640
and I've asked it again to solve P(x) = 0, and&nbsp;
it's come up with a better value. So here's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:07.610
same kind of thing as we had before, but now&nbsp;
we have some more digits. So is this the right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.610 --> 00:18:14.870
answer? Well, it's a better answer; at least&nbsp;
it's more accurate. If we plug this, however,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:21.140
into the polynomial and actually evaluate it,&nbsp;
our computer will tell us that we get something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:21.140 --> 00:18:30.980
that is about -4.8376541 x 10⁻²⁰. But it's not&nbsp;
exactly what we get—there are more digits here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.980 --> 00:18:34.820
but this is to eight decimal places.&nbsp;
That's what we get. In particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:37.850
we're not getting something that's zero. We're&nbsp;
getting something that's getting small because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.850 --> 00:18:43.790
that's 10⁻²⁰, so it's a very small quantity,&nbsp;
but it's definitely not zero. And this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:43.790 --> 00:18:50.960
the reality of it, again—this is the reality&nbsp;
that yes, you can get more and more digits,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:57.860
and so you're getting closer and closer to&nbsp;
having a number that you can plug in here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:57.860 --> 00:19:06.110
to get zero, but you cannot actually&nbsp;
get such a number. You cannot get it.

00:19:07.550 --> 00:19:16.340
So this is why discussions of this in&nbsp;
undergraduate texts are always kind of limited.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:23.330
People don't want to explore this very clearly and&nbsp;
carefully because then undergraduates would start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:28.790
to go, "Well, wait a minute, you're claiming that&nbsp;
there's a number that is a zero on this thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.790 --> 00:19:34.610
but you can't actually exhibit such a number, so&nbsp;
why should we believe the arguments? Maybe there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:34.610 --> 00:19:40.550
some problem here." Well, yes, there is a problem,&nbsp;
okay? There's a very serious problem logically.

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:46.430
Alright, so here's my claim—Wildberger's&nbsp;
claim—but in direct contradiction to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.430 --> 00:19:54.320
fundamental theorem of algebra part one: there&nbsp;
is, in fact, no number R in C satisfying P(R),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:54.320 --> 00:20:04.220
which is R⁵ - 2R + 3 = 0. I claim there is no&nbsp;
such number. This is in direct contradiction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.220 --> 00:20:11.000
to the fundamental theorem of algebra. I do&nbsp;
not dispute that there are complex numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.160
that you could plug in here, and you would&nbsp;
get something that's close to zero. I do not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:20.840
dispute that at all; I'm happy to believe&nbsp;
that. I'm happy to believe that you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:25.850
get values here for which this thing is some&nbsp;
very, very small complex number that's very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:34.070
very close to zero. But problem: you cannot find a&nbsp;
number R, a complex number R, such that P(R) = 0.

00:20:34.070 --> 00:20:40.040
So this is a very direct claim, isn't it?&nbsp;
I mean, we're not talking about philosophy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:44.870
here—it's not a question of opinion. It's&nbsp;
not something that someone can say, "Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.870 --> 00:20:50.720
I have an axiomatic position that says such&nbsp;
and such." I'm making a very direct claim about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:57.380
the existence of a solution to a polynomial&nbsp;
equation, and I challenge any mathematician&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:57.380 --> 00:21:06.620
to prove me wrong. And you can prove me wrong&nbsp;
by showing us a number R, a complex number R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:11.570
that I can then plug in and check. So you&nbsp;
can do whatever you like and use all kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:11.570 --> 00:21:17.300
sophisticated cohomological theories if you like,&nbsp;
but at the end of it, you have to give me an R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:17.300 --> 00:21:22.950
and I'm going to take that R and plug it&nbsp;
into P(R), and I'm going to see whether&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:29.640
or not your R actually works. And I claim&nbsp;
that it's not going to work. It's just not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:36.660
going to work. And so the fundamental theorem&nbsp;
of algebra is incorrect. It is just not true.

00:21:36.660 --> 00:21:43.590
Well, there will be people who will say, "Well,&nbsp;
wait a minute, Norman, I can exhibit such an R&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:49.650
for you. What you do is you start doing this&nbsp;
procedure, okay? You do this, and then you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.650 --> 00:21:54.030
do this, and then you do this, and you keep on&nbsp;
going to infinity, and at the end of infinity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:54.030 --> 00:22:01.590
you will have such an R." So they will give us a&nbsp;
prescription for finding such an R that involves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.590 --> 00:22:07.680
an infinite number of steps. Now, I'm not able to&nbsp;
do an infinite number of steps, so I'm not happy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:13.920
to be given such a prescription. But if someone&nbsp;
has such a philosophy towards finding such an R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:19.260
then I suggest that they themselves carry out&nbsp;
the infinite number of steps, and after they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:19.260 --> 00:22:26.550
have done so, then they can exhibit the end result&nbsp;
to us, alright? So I'm not interested in someone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:26.550 --> 00:22:33.630
telling me a procedure that will find such an R;&nbsp;
I'm interested in someone actually exhibiting such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.630 --> 00:22:40.590
an R directly. That's not going to happen. That's&nbsp;
why the fundamental theorem of algebra is wrong.

00:22:40.590 --> 00:22:45.930
And for a very similar reason, the second version&nbsp;
of the fundamental theorem of algebra doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:53.310
work either. So if we take our same polynomial and&nbsp;
ask our computer for all of the complex zeros, it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:58.440
will give us some answers. So it will give us the&nbsp;
number that we've already seen, and it will give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:05.130
us also four other ones, which are not visible on&nbsp;
the graph that we drew, okay? They're not actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:05.130 --> 00:23:10.440
corresponding to places where the graph crosses&nbsp;
the x-axis because we're talking about complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:16.740
values. But nevertheless, here are these complex&nbsp;
numbers that have a property that when you plug&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:23.250
them in, you get something that's very close to&nbsp;
being the complex number zero, like zero plus zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:30.690
i. But notice that these things here have the same&nbsp;
aspect as this one does. So I'm putting three dots&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:30.690 --> 00:23:37.050
here now to represent the fact that my computer&nbsp;
actually has a range of possible things that it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:42.630
can give me depending on the resolution level that&nbsp;
I've asked it for. It doesn't give me a unique&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:52.500
answer; it depends on how many digits I have asked&nbsp;
it to give me an answer for, so it's a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:57.000
open-ended. But nevertheless, there's something in&nbsp;
this direction—your computer will find something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:01.890
in this direction as well. So there's this&nbsp;
one plus i, then the same values, really,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:01.890 --> 00:24:07.350
minus i. Now, these are called complex conjugate&nbsp;
pairs, and then there's another pair like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:07.350 --> 00:24:13.290
involving these two numbers, plus and minus, and&nbsp;
here's a number, which are the coefficients of i.

00:24:13.290 --> 00:24:21.210
Okay, so in the same way, this is very explicit,&nbsp;
really. If the fundamental theorem of algebra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:27.330
part two really did work, then we could write&nbsp;
our polynomial as a product of linear factors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:33.240
and the linear factors would correspond exactly&nbsp;
to these five numbers. So we could form the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:42.540
expression (x - R₁)(x - R₂)(x - R₃)(x - R₄)(x&nbsp;
- R₅), and you can do this. You can plug the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:42.540 --> 00:24:47.850
values that you had in—that will necessarily&nbsp;
mean making a choice. You know, your computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:47.850 --> 00:24:52.770
will give you a certain number of digits, and&nbsp;
you will have to use that certain number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:59.340
digits in order to create these linear factors.&nbsp;
And then you can get your computer to evaluate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.340 --> 00:25:05.670
that product, and you will see that you have&nbsp;
a polynomial that is pretty close to this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.670 --> 00:25:12.180
in the sense that the difference between these&nbsp;
two polynomials is another polynomial with very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:18.720
small coefficients—you know, the coefficients&nbsp;
are like 10⁻⁸ or 10⁻²⁰ or something like that.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:18.720 --> 00:25:24.630
So these things are very close to being the&nbsp;
same polynomial, but they're not actually the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:30.870
same polynomial. The fundamental theorem&nbsp;
of algebra part two does not work either.

00:25:30.870 --> 00:25:39.360
Now, does this render all those applications of&nbsp;
the fundamental theorem to physics and chemistry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:49.560
and industry and so on wrong? No, not at all,&nbsp;
because the applied mathematician doesn't need the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:57.030
pure form of the fundamental theorem. They only&nbsp;
need the approximate form. They only need to know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.030 --> 00:26:04.020
that we can find complex numbers such that this&nbsp;
thing is very close to this. They only need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:09.060
find a zero in the sense that we have some number&nbsp;
so that when we plug in, we get a number that is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.060 --> 00:26:15.690
very close to zero. To an engineer, if something&nbsp;
is zero to eight or twenty decimal places,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:20.520
then it's effectively zero for them. They&nbsp;
don't care if theoretically it's not zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:28.290
right? So the fundamental theorem of algebra is&nbsp;
always going to be an important and useful tool&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:28.290 --> 00:26:35.850
for applied mathematicians. The question is, how&nbsp;
shall we pure mathematicians understand it? How&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:35.850 --> 00:26:42.450
shall we think about what's really going on? This&nbsp;
is a huge challenge for modern mathematics and,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:48.690
in fact, a challenge that has very, very&nbsp;
big ramifications for abstract algebra.

00:26:48.690 --> 00:26:56.250
So we'll talk more next time about how we can&nbsp;
move forward on this challenge. What is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:56.250 --> 00:27:02.790
fundamental theorem of algebra really? What can&nbsp;
we actually aspire to in terms of setting it up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:02.790 --> 00:27:09.330
correctly? I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:27:10.980 --> 00:27:11.980
[Music

